Your radio analogy points to another interesting distinction.

The waves may already exist, but a receiver determines which subset becomes experience.

A radio doesn’t create the station.

It creates access.

Likewise, our senses don’t reveal everything that exists. They reveal what our biology has evolved—or been built—to detect. Infrared, ultraviolet, magnetic fields, and many frequencies pass by us unnoticed without instruments.

That makes me wonder if “thinking” is partly the construction of new receivers. Mathematics, microscopes, telescopes, and languages all extend what we can tune into. They don’t necessarily create new realities; they expand the range of patterns we can perceive and reason about.

