On your last point, I think we’re mostly talking about emphasis rather than disagreement.

When you say:

“We’re doing precisely as much as is needed for the time and purpose.”

I hear a principle of adaptive abstraction.

Sometimes the right move is to work at a very general level because you’re searching for candidate invariants. At that stage, you’re generating hypotheses and looking for recurring structure. Later, those hypotheses can be specialized and tested against the details of particular domains.

That’s a productive workflow as long as each stage is recognized for what it is: exploration first, validation afterward. The level of abstraction should match the task.

